Programming Language Mascots
===============================================================================

%% Programming language mascots have become an integral part of the programming community, serving as symbols of identity, culture, and fun for various languages. From the historic Logo Turtle to Ferris the crab for Rust, these mascots not only represent their respective languages but also foster a sense of community among developers. In this article, we will explore the history, significance, and impact of programming language mascots, highlighting some of the most iconic ones and their contributions to the programming world. We'll cover their origins, design inspirations, and the role they play in marketing and community building.

***

I've looked around, I can't find any good articles on the history of programming language mascots. So I thought I'd write one!

This article tries to cover the past present and future of programming language mascots, exploring their origins, significance, and impact on the programming community.

We'll look at the most iconic mascots, their design inspirations, and how they contribute to the identity and culture of programming languages. We'll also look at some newer mascots and trends in mascot design, as well as the role of mascots in marketing and community building.

This kind of topic collects knowledge that may only be contained in scattered blog posts, forum discussions, and social media threads, so I hope this article serves as a comprehensive resource for anyone interested in the fascinating world of programming language mascots. If I've gotten any of the history wrong, let me know, I'd like this post to be accurate and authoritative for this topic.


1. History of mascots in computing
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Computing used to be a largely academic, business, and military endeavor and therefore serious in nature. But that of course never stopped people and subcultures within computing from having fun and expressing themselves creatively, and sometime even in silly ways. As the field grew and diversified -- and also commercialized -- the need for branding and user engagement led to the widespread adoption of mascots. Moreover, programming languages began to form communities of users around them, and mascots served as a way to foster a sense of identity to help the community bond and express their shared identity under the language's banner.

REDDit USER ASKS WHY DO PROGRAMMING LANGUAGES HAVE MASCOTS?

Good question! 

- Branding and Marketing: Mascots help create a memorable image for a programming language, making it easier for developers to recognize and remember it among many options.
- Community Building: Mascots can foster a sense of community and belonging among users of a programming language, helping to create a shared identity.
- Engagement and Fun: Mascots add an element of fun and personality to a programming language, making it more approachable and engaging for users.
- Differentiation: In a crowded market of programming languages, mascots help differentiate one language from another, making it stand out.
- Cultural Significance: Mascots can embody the values, philosophy, or characteristics of a programming language, reflecting its design principles or intended use cases.

But when it comes down to it, they're just fun. Programming languages are abstract concepts, and mascots give them a tangible, relatable form that can make them more representable in forms like logos, merchandise, and documentation.

So let's take a look at the history of programming language mascots and some of the most iconic ones out there!

The idea of applying mascot branding to computing products dates back to 1976 when BSD Unix adopted the BSD Daemon, also known as Beastie, as its mascot [BEASTIE]. The character was created by artist Marshall Kirk McKusick and has since become one of the most recognizable symbols in the Unix community.

Designed by:

Phil Foglio
Mike O'Brien
John Lasseter

https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tux_(mascot)

In this case the mascot is a daemon as an allusion to the idea of a background process in Unix systems, which are often referred to as "daemons." This started the tradition of using the mascot to represent and personify features of the operating system, although as we'll see the origin stories and meanings behind them can have varying levels of depth. 

Since the introduction of the BSD Daemon, the open source community has frequently used mascots to represent various projects and movements including the GNU Project's GNU (a wildebeest), Linux's Tux the penguin, Glenda the Plan 9 bunny, the Android robot, and many others [^1].

2. Proto Mascots
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Mascots were not always a feature in programming languages. In the early days of computing, programming languages were primarily designed for professional use by scientists, engineers, and mathematicians, and they lacked the playful and approachable elements that mascots would later bring to languages.

The earliest programming language names were acronyms or abbreviations that described their purpose or functionality, such as Fortran (Formula Translation), COBOL (Common Business-Oriented Language), and LISP (LISt Processing). These names were often chosen for their technical accuracy rather than their marketability or appeal to a broader audience. Even the first langauge Plankalkül, created by Konrad Zuse in the 1940s, simply described what it was -- a plan calculus. It wasn't until lthe Logo language that names began to represent more than just technical functionality, but instead aimed to evoke a philosophy or even just a feeling embodied by the language.

It's not a coincidence then that that Logo introduced what can be reasonably construed as the first programming langauge mascot: the Logo turtle. Now, at this time I'd like to create a brief taxonomy for mascots, because there are really two distinct types of mascots that we'll see throughout programming language history. 

The first is the "proper-mascot", which is what we all think of when we think of a mascot: it's a distinct character with a name, a personality, it usually has a backstory, and is used consistently and officially by the language's community or creators. Examples include Java's Duke, Rust's Ferris, and the Go Gopher.

The second variety we will call "quasi-mascots", which are more like symbols or logos that have taken on a mascot-like role in the community, but lack the full characteristics of a proper mascot. They may not have a name, personality, or backstory, and their use may be more informal or unofficial. Examples include Python's python, Perl's camel, and Swift's swift. These are icons of the langauge, but they they lack that certain personality and consistency that makes them true mascots.

What we see in the history of programming langauges is that the earliest mascots were quasi-mascots, and over time as the culture of programming languages evolved, proper mascots began to emerge as these quasi-mascots became more developed and popular ways to represent programming langauge communities.

(1.1) Logo's Turtle (1967)

"body syntonic reasoning." William Gray Walter 

So when did programming languages start getting mascots of their own?

The first programming language mascot is arguably the Logo turtle, which was introduced in the late 1960s as part of the Logo programming language. 

https://youtu.be/cwnMhI9XjO8?si=FV8zG9Tj6PHoqrjg&t=614

Before Logo, programming languages were primarily designed for professional use by scientists, engineers, and mathematicians. Languages like Fortran (1957), COBOL (1959), and LISP (1958) were created to solve specific problems in their respective domains, and they lacked the playful and approachable elements that mascots would later bring to langauges, even the corporate ones.

Originally, the turtle was a physical robot that could be programmed to move around and draw shapes, but it later evolved into a graphical representation on computer screens called Turtle Graphics, which is what most people think of when they recall Logo [TURTLE]. The idea behind Logo was that it was designed to be more accessible to children by taking advantage of their natural ability to understand spatial relationships and movement. Whereas most languages of the time (and still today really) expected a level of abstract reasoning that was beyond the level of children, logo sought to meet them at their level by providing a visual and interactive way to learn programming concepts.

The turtle was essentially the programmer's avatar in the programming environment, giving them a tangible way to see the results of their code, and allowed them to debug by putting themselves in the turtle's shoes and reasoning from its perspective. This design allowed Logo to be used by children as young as four years old, making it one of the earliest examples of a programming language designed specifically for educational purposes.

The turtle got its name[^2] from the physical turtle robots used in the early implementations of the Logo language, some of which featured a dome-like enclosure that resembled a turtle's shell. The turtle mascot has since become an iconic symbol of the Logo programming language and is often used in educational materials and programming environments that support Logo. Even the Turtle robot has lived on in the Open Robotics Initiative, which has released a TurtleBot series of robots for education and research.

https://www.alancsmith.co.uk/logo/

3. Age of Mascots
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Just as programming language names evolved from technical acronyms to more playful and evocative names, programming language mascots also evolved from simple symbols to more fully developed characters with personalities and backstories. This shift was driven by the growing importance of branding and marketing in the software industry to differentiate programming languages in a crowded market and to foster a sense of community among developers. 

The 1990s marked the first true programming language mascot, Duke, which was followed by a wave of mascots in the 2000s and 2010s as programming languages became more mainstream and commercialized. In this section, we'll take a look at some of the most iconic programming language mascots that emerged during this period, including Java's Duke, Go's Gopher, Rust's Ferris, and Scratch's ScratchCat. If your favoriate mascot is not listed in this section, don't worry we try to be more comprehensive in (§6).

(2.3) Java's Duke (1992)

Java's Duke mascot was the first programming language mascot to get the full corporate makeover. Introduced in 1995 by Sun Microsystems, Duke was designed to represent the Java programming language and its platform [CHANDER]. Duke was created by *Joe Palrang*, an animator who went on to work at Dreamworks on movies like Shrek. So of course Duke is exactly the kind of character you'd expect from a professional animator. 

> Duke was the interactive host that enabled a new type of user interface that went beyond the buttons, mice, and pop-up menus of the desktop computing world - Sharat Chander, Director, Java SE Product Management

This marks a new moment in the history of programming language mascots, the first time they began to be used not just for community building and fun, but also as part of a broader marketing strategy to promote the language and its ecosystem. Duke didn't represent any particular feature of Java per se, but rather embodied the traits of a good mascot first: friendly, approachable, and versatile, and since Java targeted a broad range of customers, not objectionable to the sensibilities of any particular group.

It's not quite clear what Duke actually *is* though, which was kind of the trend at the time in all kinds of media [^3]. His form is a two-toend triangular body, a big red nose, and two hands. His nondescript appearance was meant to be simple and versatile, allowing him to be put in various contexts and situations. Although in one of the comics he is called a "tooth" which he says he hates as people mistake him for one all the time.

Duke was often depicted in various poses and scenarios, showcasing his versatility and adaptability, which is what you want in a good mascot. They even released a comic at one point in which Duke is misteaken as the culprit of a theft of "JIT Cola", but it turns out it's his evil twin brother "Fang" (further giving credence to the idea that Duke is some kind of tooth), who attempts to murder him.

Although Duke started out owned entirely by Sun Microsystems, when Oracle acquired Sun in 2010, they inherited the rights to Duke. Recognizing the importance of Duke to the Java community, Oracle decided to "open source" Duke, making his likeness available for public use under certain conditions. Which really is what a mascot should be -- community representation.

