(5.8) Python's Python

You could possibly consider a snake to be mascot of the Python language, but there's really no canonical character that's associated with Python. 

Indeed, the Python name doesn't even refer to a kind of snake[^4], but rather to Monty Python, the British comedy troupe. Because of this, for a long time Python eschewed having a snake mascot. It wasn't until 2005 that the Python Software Foundation held a contest to design an official mascot for the language, which resulted in several snake-themed designs. However, none of these designs were ever officially adopted as the language's mascot.

So while snakes are often used in Python branding -- logos and various supporting tools and packages (e.g. Anaconda) -- there isn't a specific python character that represents the Python language in the same way as Duke represents Java or Ferris represents Rust.

https://www.thecodingforums.com/threads/proposed-python-logo.356848/
https://groups.google.com/g/comp.lang.python/c/rh7qT7lQWys/m/ypoPn8QdQ9wJ

