[^1]: Why doesn't Windows have a mascot, you might be wondering? Well, there *are* several unofficial Windows mascots created by fans called [OS-tans](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/OS-tan), anime anthropomorphizations of the various Windows operating systems that have been popular in fringe internet culture. It started when users of Windows ME started drawing anthropomorphized characters to represent the operating system, often portraying it as a girl with a somewhat unstable personality, which is supposed to reflect the reputation Windows ME had for being buggy and unreliable. I had started looking into this but it gets very weird very fast, so I'll leave it as an exercise for the reader to delve into that rabbit hole.

[^2]: The Logo turtle doesn't actually have a proper name, but if I had to pick one I would choose Plato.

[^3]: Remember Izzy, the mascot of the 1996 Atlanta Olympics? What the heck was that even?

[^4]: This is confusing much in the same way that the name Rust does not actually refer to oxidized iron, but rather to a fungus that grows on apples. Mirroring the same situation in Python, there are many Rust crates that are themed after industrial or metallic concepts (e.g. Iron the web framework), but not really any mold-themed crates of note.

[^5]: C++'s Keith the Diseased Rat
There's an urban legends that C++'s mascot is a diseased rat named Keith who blew his leg off with a shotgun, referring to the tendancy for C++ users to "shoot themselves in the foot" due to the language's complexity and potential for errors. 
Part of the rumor is that it was created by GNU founder Richard Stallman as a way to criticize C++ for its complexity and potential for misuse.
However, this is not true; Keith is not an official mascot, but more of a physical manifestation of C++'s spirit on in our material realm.
https://lunduke.locals.com/post/5111104/no-the-c-mascot-is-not-a-diseased-rat-named-keith

[^6]: I almost didn't include the .Net Bot because it's more of a general mascot for the .Net ecosystem, and we did say this list was specifically for programming languages. However, since Mika, being a round mechanical thing with arms and legs, vaguely resembles the .Net Bot, I thought it would be worth including as a point of comparison. Also to note specifically Mika is based on a sketch of a tattoo a friend had drawn for me many years ago, so the resemblance is purely coincidental.

